As I wrote in a previous post, 

    According to "Rose is a toolkit for writing, editing and running application configurations." In essence, Rose is a wrapper to Cylc which is designed to make that software more user friendly.

As of version 4.X, Rose replaces the namelist... as the recommended way of running JULES. It is still possible to run JULES in this way... but using Rose has a number of advantages. In-built version control (provided by `fcm`) and so on. Rose comes with a GUI that you may want to use. However, I prefer working from the command line. I have put together a short guide on using Rose in this way. It is non-exhaustive and only covers the commands I use on a regular basis. The programs I use (`rose`, `fcm`, and `svn`) have extensive documentation so please do consult these for additional information.

## Getting hold of a Rose suite
The best way to develop a new JULES application is to modify an existing Rose suite. To download a suite from the Met Office repository use `rosie checkout <suite-name>`. In the remainder of this post I will be working from a copy of Toby Marthews' Rose suite... which we can checkout by entering the following command:
```bash
rosie checkout u-am539
```
See the `rosie checkout` [documentation](https://metomi.github.io/rose/doc/html/api/command-reference.html#command-rosie-checkout) for more information.

