## Version control
As I mentioned in a previous post, `fcm` is a version control system... It is a good idea to make use of this facility when working... There are several things you can do... Here I focus on three of the most common things... Committing changes, seeing commit history, and returning to a previous commit.

### Commit changes

Commit changes using the following command:
```bash
fcm commit
```

### See commit history
It is useful to be able to see the commit history for the current branch. There are a couple of commands which are used for this purpose. To print information about the branch, including the most recent commit message if `--verbose` is enabled, use `fcm branch-info` (http://cms.ncas.ac.uk/chrome/site/FCM/user_guide/command_ref.html#fcm-branch-info):

```bash
fcm branch-info --verbose
```

To print all the commit log messages, use `svn log` (pipe to `less` to see one screen at a time):

```bash
svn log | less
```

